ndya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Emma de Dunstanville was born in 1135, in Castle Combe, Wiltshire, England, her father, Alan Reginald de Dunstanville, was 31 and her mother, Isabel FitzReginald, was 43. She married Sir William de Englefield in 1154, in Englefield, Berkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1184, in Lichtenberg, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1135–1184":"1135–1184","1135–1186":"1135–1186","1143–1190":"1143–1190","1110–1190":"1110–1190","1154–1226":"1154–1226","1154–Male":"1154–Surnud","1105–1150":"1105–1150","1093–Female":"1093–Surnud","1190":"1190","3 April 1150":"3. aprill 1150","1154":"1154","1110":"1110","1143":"1143","1186":"1186","1184":"1184","1150":"1150","1093":"1093","1105":"1105","1226":"1226","ABT 1154":"umbes 1154","1